{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657490"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:29:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:29:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20500"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20500"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13373"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92600"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13373"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20500"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75940"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11582"},{"type":"tags","id":"11744"},{"type":"tags","id":"12431"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31728"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31729"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92600"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the correct sequence of events in autophagy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct engulfment of organelles by lysosomes","Phagophore nucleation followed by autophagosome formation","Random degradation of cytoplasmic contents without membrane formation","Autophagosome formation followed by phagophore nucleation","Lysosomal fusion followed by isolation membrane formation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct sequence of events in autophagy begins with \u003Cstrong\u003Ephagophore nucleation followed by autophagosome formation\u003C/strong\u003E. Autophagy proceeds through several distinct steps:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003ENucleation and formation of an isolation membrane (phagophore), typically derived from the endoplasmic reticulum\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFormation of an autophagosome from the isolation membrane, which sequesters intracellular organelles and cytosolic structures\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMaturation of the autophagosome by fusion with lysosomes to form an autophagolysosome\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDegradation of the contents by lysosomal enzymes\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELysosomal fusion followed by isolation membrane formation\u003C/strong\u003E - This reverses the correct sequence; lysosomes fuse with already-formed autophagosomes, not before membrane formation begins\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutophagosome formation followed by phagophore nucleation\u003C/strong\u003E - This reverses the correct sequence; the phagophore (isolation membrane) must form first before it can develop into an autophagosome\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect engulfment of organelles by lysosomes\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes a different process; autophagy requires the intermediate formation of autophagosomes rather than direct lysosomal engulfment\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandom degradation of cytoplasmic contents without membrane formation\u003C/strong\u003E - Autophagy is not random but involves selective targeting of cargo and requires membrane formation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAutophagy is regulated by autophagy-related genes (Atgs) and involves the lipidation of microtubule-associated protein light chain 3 (LC3) with phosphatidylethanolamine. This process is important for cellular homeostasis and is implicated in various diseases including cancer, neurodegenerative disorders, and inflammatory bowel disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Autophagy is a cellular process where cytoplasmic materials are delivered to lysosomes for degradation, allowing cells to recycle their components during nutrient deprivation.","The autophagy process involves formation of an isolation membrane (phagophore), development of an autophagosome, and fusion with lysosomes to form an autophagolysosome.","Autophagy plays important roles in cellular homeostasis, stress response, and is implicated in various diseases including cancer, neurodegenerative disorders, and inflammatory bowel disease."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. p. 48."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75940"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20500"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75940"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-18T14:36:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T14:36:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13373"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92600"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11582"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Cell injury, cell death and adaptations","synonyms":[],"description":null,"p